    slug: 'commercial-siding-northern-california-guide',
    title: "Commercial Siding in Northern California: What Property Owners and GCs Need to Know",
    excerpt: "Planning a commercial siding project in the North State? Here is what matters most — materials, timelines, coordination, and why experience with NorCal conditions makes a difference.",
    content: `
      <p>Commercial siding projects in Northern California come with a specific set of challenges that differ from residential work. Scale, scheduling coordination with other trades, code requirements, and material performance in an extreme climate all factor into how a project runs and how the finished product holds up.</p>

      <p>Whether you are a general contractor subcontracting a siding scope, a property manager planning an exterior renovation, or a commercial property owner replacing failing siding on a retail building or multi-unit complex, this guide covers what you need to know about commercial siding in the North State.</p>

      <h2>Material Options for Commercial Applications</h2>

      <img src="https://vibe.filesafe.space/1777345871363473576/assets/459e268e-bc09-44a5-baf2-77ea643e1b61.png" alt="Commercial siding installation in Northern California" />

      <h3>Fiber Cement</h3>
      <p>James Hardie and other fiber cement products are the leading choice for commercial siding in fire-prone areas of Northern California. Non-combustible, Class A fire-rated, and dimensionally stable in Redding's extreme heat, fiber cement is appropriate for virtually any commercial application. It holds paint well, resists insects and rot, and satisfies most commercial building code requirements for exterior wall assemblies in WUI zones. For commercial buildings in Shasta County, Butte County, and other high-risk areas, fiber cement is increasingly the default specification.</p>

      <h3>Metal Siding Panels</h3>
      <p>Metal siding — steel, aluminum, or zinc panels — is a popular choice for industrial buildings, retail structures, and modern commercial developments. Metal is non-combustible, extremely durable, and requires minimal maintenance. Modern metal panel systems allow for a wide range of aesthetic expressions from industrial corrugated to architectural standing seam. Panel systems also allow for efficient installation, which can be important on large-square-footage commercial projects where labor efficiency drives project economics.</p>

      <h3>Engineered Wood</h3>
      <p>Engineered wood siding products like LP SmartSide offer a wood-aesthetic appearance with improved moisture resistance over solid wood. They are appropriate for commercial applications where a traditional wood look is desired and cost constraints preclude fiber cement. Note that engineered wood is not non-combustible — it is treated to improve fire performance but does not carry the same fire rating as fiber cement or metal. For WUI commercial properties, fiber cement or metal is generally preferred.</p>

      <h3>Vinyl</h3>
      <p>Vinyl siding is generally not our recommendation for commercial applications in the North State. As noted in our residential siding guide, vinyl is essentially plastic — it melts, oils cans in extreme heat, and cannot be repainted when it fades. On a commercial property where appearance and durability reflect on the business and the property value, vinyl's performance limitations become quickly visible. We install vinyl where clients specifically request it and budget requires it, but we're transparent about its limitations upfront.</p>

      <h2>Coordination with General Contractors</h2>

      <p>If you're a GC managing a commercial build or renovation, siding is typically one of many exterior trades you're coordinating. The qualities that make a siding subcontractor easy to work with on a commercial site are different from what matters on a residential project.</p>

      <h3>Clear Bids with Defined Scope</h3>
      <p>Ambiguous bids create change order disputes. A well-written commercial siding bid should specify materials by product name and spec, define the scope of substrate preparation, identify what weather barrier product is being installed, and clearly define what is and isn't included in the base price. When reviewing bids, vague "allowances" for flashing or substrate repairs are a red flag.</p>

      <h3>Realistic Scheduling</h3>
      <p>Siding crews need to coordinate with framing, windows, roofing, and painting. Over-promising on schedule leads to rushed work, quality issues, and schedule pressure on other trades. We build schedules honestly and communicate proactively when conditions or upstream delays affect our timeline.</p>

      <h3>Jobsite Professionalism</h3>
      <p>Commercial sites have safety requirements that differ from residential. We maintain OSHA safety compliance, keep our work areas clean, and coordinate with site superintendents on staging, material delivery, and access needs.</p>

      <h2>Property Manager Considerations</h2>

      <p>For property managers overseeing commercial or multi-unit residential properties, exterior siding replacement requires managing tenant impact, maintaining property appearance throughout the project, and ensuring the work is completed within budget and timeline without disrupting operations.</p>

      <p>Key questions to ask a siding contractor before signing a contract:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>How do you handle dust, debris, and site cleanup throughout the project?</li>
        <li>How will access to tenant spaces be managed and communicated?</li>
        <li>What is your protocol for unexpected substrate damage discovered during removal?</li>
        <li>Are you carrying appropriate insurance for the project type and size?</li>
        <li>What warranty do you provide on workmanship, separate from the product warranty?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Commercial Siding in Northern California's Fire-Risk Environment</h2>

      <p>Commercial properties in the North State face the same fire-season exposure risks as residential properties — but the consequences of exterior ignition on a commercial building can include business interruption, tenant displacement, and significant liability exposure in addition to property loss.</p>

      <p>Commercial buildings in or near WUI zones in Shasta County, Butte County, and Tehama County are subject to the same Chapter 7A requirements as residential construction for new builds and substantial renovations. Working with a contractor who understands these requirements and can specify appropriate materials that satisfy them is essential for code compliance and meaningful fire risk reduction.</p>

      <h2>Getting a Commercial Bid</h2>

      <p><strong>O'Brien Mountain Home</strong> provides commercial siding installation and repair across Northern California. We work with general contractors, property managers, facility managers, and commercial property owners. Our bids are clear, our communication is direct, and we understand the conditions and requirements specific to the North State market.</p>
    `,
